7 ways to get your ten minutes of stretching…

✨ Put it in your calendar; electronic or paper, the exact time that you plan to stretch. There are no rain checks unless there’s a catastrophe. 📅 ⏰
✨ Do it anywhere at anytime, spontaneously. There was never a better time than now, reading this caption. I see you 👀 
✨ Make a stretching date with a fitness buddy or someone who could use a buddy. 🥂 
✨ Figure out a way to make it part of your routine and second nature, like doing the dishes. So hard to get started but so good once you have.
✨ Show up 20 minutes early to rehearsal or practice to stretch
✨ Start a stretching club in your area or over Zoom with your friends
✨ Touch base with a coach that you trust to get your stretchy juices flowing ➿
✨ Get your kids involved, “wanna stretch with me?!” or recruit your significant other to make sure that you get your 10 minutes of stretching every day

“Every season is one of becoming, but not always one of blooming. Be gracious with your ever-evolving self.” — B. Oakman

Life happens and it means that we can only take it one day at a time. If you’re in a phase of life where training has been nearly impossible, I see you and I feel you.  “Be aware of what season you are in and give yourself the grace to be there.” — Kristen Dalton

Top 3 reasons to get out of your lower back today:

✨ It never feels good 🤷‍♀️
✨ It practically is ✨always ✨ able and willing to bend first and do the majority of the muscular work. Take the time to clarify how to best use your upper and middle back in backbends.
✨ It’s a ticking time bomb 💣 // just because something doesn’t bother us today, tomorrow or in 2 years, doesn’t mean that it won’t eventually catch up to us. We wouldn’t use our lower back as the primary mover to lift a heavy box, why would we use it to move half of our body?

If you’re curious to learn more, we break down full spine and core technique for backbends at virtual Contortion Club 🦸🤸‍♂️ flexibility and handstand bootcamp, every Monday and Friday online. Link in my bio for current sign up information. All levels are welcome 🙏☺️

66 days to journey to your back bending dreams ✨☄️

“A habit is a routine or behaviour that is performed regularly and, in many cases, automatically. With the same habits, you’ll end up with the same results. But with better habits, anything is possible.

On average, it takes more than 2 months before a new behavior becomes automatic — 66 days to be exact. And how long it takes a new habit to form can vary widely depending on the behavior, the person, and the circumstances.

We all deal with setbacks but in the long run the quality of our lives often depends on the quality of our habits.

Embracing longer timelines can help us realize that habits are a process and not an event. All of the “21 Days” hype can make it really easy to think, “Oh, I’ll just do this and it’ll be done.” But habits never work that way. You have to embrace the process. You have to commit to the system.

—- @jamesclear, author of #AtomicHabits

We are here for it. The weekly grind of getting getting your flexibility and handstand goals accomplished. Deep down, we know that these things take time, and sometimes we wish that our lives had more space and less noise and….more time (🙋‍♀️).

My top 3 chest stand thoughts (currently) 👇

❤️‍🔥1. Find a balance of frequency and recovery. Depending on where you’re at with your personal training. You’ll need to continuously experiment and adjust depending on you life circumstances and personal needs. Whether it’s 1 day on, 1 day off/recovery (soft tissue, light movement), or 3 days on, 3 days off and 1 day recovery. Keep playing and tweaking with what makes sense for you.

❤️‍🔥2. Soft tissue, soft tissue, soft tissue work. It’s not the end all, be all answer to everything, but when you are either A) training other disciplines such as aerial, pole, figure skating, CrossFit, ballet, stunt work, etc and/or B) have a demanding desk job, we all need to “undo” the previous hours or previous days of whatever our body had to endure — whether that was a LOT of activity or NO activity. Soft tissue gives you a neurological and psychological “clean slate”. It doesn’t have to be 1 hour long (thought it could be) — but if you sense that  there is no way you can do any backbending, after soft tissue work (partnered with breath work — ALWAYS), I promise that you’ll feel at least a little less hesitant.

❤️‍🔥3.  Learn to activate your back (coil) in your backbends, but also learn to totally relax your back in your backbends. You need to be able to do both at different times. This is nuanced and takes time to understand in various backbending skills.

Remember, flexibility and contortion training can be physically demanding, so it’s crucial to prioritize safety and work at your own pace. Seeking guidance from a qualified contortion instructor or coach can provide valuable guidance and help ensure proper technique and progress.

About UYS DU BUISSON @uysbook, my co-teacher:
Uys (pronounced “Ace”) is a multi-disciplinary circus artist and actor. He has also been a teacher for over 2 decades. He is passionate about sharing the knowledge he has gained in a career dedicated to performing in productions that blend theatrical storytelling with daring physicality
Uys’s most recent performance credits include: The Beatles LOVE by Cirque Du Soleil (5 years), the North American tour of Odysseo by Cavalia, the national tour of Peter Pan 360 (choreographed by Gypsy Snider of The 7 Fingers) and Company XIV’s Nutcracker Rouge.
Originally from Cape Town, South Africa, he grew up training and performing with a contemporary circus company. His love for theatre brought him to New York where he studied acting at the Circle in the Square conservatory. He spent a decade in the city performing in all kinds of unconventional projects, from site-specific work with Noemie Lafrance to Elizabeth Streb’s large scale productions. Uys has conceived, directed and performed many of his own multimedia projects and is continuing to explore the intersection of theatre and circus in his performance and teaching.

The most surprising thing about contortion forearm-stands when getting back to them is how HEAVY they are.  Research has shown there are similar muscular adaptations for flexibility training as strength training, such as increased muscle strength and thickness — though this is not widely discussed beyond nerdy flexibility and strength circles.  A month of contortion forearmstands and handstands. What began as super heavy and impossible feeling, in regards to the back-bending in particular, has become manageable! Of course 4 weeks is nothing within the scope of training a skill but it’s nice to have this measurement and see how far you can take a particular set of shapes in a set amount of time.

Tomorrow we finalize this revolution around this contortion forearmstands and handstands and next week we move on to needle varieties! 🔥🔥🔥

“Sporting Fashion” is the first exhibition to explore the evolution of women’s sporting fashion over this 160-year period. The exhibition includes 65 ensembles comprised of more than 480 historic objects selected from the exceptional collections of the FIDM Museum at the Fashion Institute of Design & Merchandising, Los Angeles.

Motorcycle gear, ski wear and bowling outfits will be among the items on display, using authentic apparel to illustrate changing interests, freedoms and social norms. The exhibition includes garments and accessories from long-established sportswear brands such as Champion and Spalding, in addition to garments and accessories from key fashion brands such as Abercrombie & Fitch, Balenciaga and Chanel.

“Sporting Fashion” will explore six themes covering leisurely outdoor pursuits, equestrian interests, beach and swimwear, winter activities, high-speed transportation, and team sports.

The exhibition also highlights the lives and accomplishments of 16 storied women in sports. Those athletes include American sprinter Wilma Rudolph, a three-time Olympic champion, and pilot Hazel Ying Lee, the first Chinese American woman to join the Women Airforce Service Pilots during World War II. ;

This exhibition is organized by the American Federation of Arts and FIDM Museum at the Fashion Institute of Design & Merchandising, Los Angeles. The presentation in Utica is made possible by Elizabeth R. Lemieux, Ph.D., the Family of F.X. Matt II, Joseph Abraham, Cheryl and Fred Haritatos, and The Hon. Joan E. Shkane (ret.).

There is an exceptional preface to the catalogue by @serenawilliams. Highly recommend that you check out the exhibit, and come see the show on September 14!

Initial late night thoughts on coming back to performing after taking 4 years off:

⚡️ The work that you have put in in the past will always be there for you. 
⚡️ BUT there will be an excavation period
⚡️ The excavation period is the real challenge. There will be weeks and maybe even months where you see no progress at all. It will make you doubt yourself, wonder if you’re too old, wonder if it’s all gone. If you stay the course though, stay patient and wise — brick by brick, I promise you that you will begin to uncover what was there all along but needed some “air and light” to bud and grow again 🌱

Thank you to all the beautiful people who I’ve been blessed to support and encourage me. Thank you for all of the incredibly touching messages of support from students, friends and locals. Thank you to @huemanbein and @munsonutica for cultivating this opportunity. Thank you, generous people of Utica, NY for welcoming this city slicker 😂

🌀✨ How resistance bands can aid in breakthrough flexibility development ✨🌀

🌀Progressive Overload🌀
✨Gradual Intensity Increase✨
Resistance bands allow for a gradual increase in intensity over time. As your flexibility improves, you can use stronger bands or increase the tension in the existing bands, providing a form of progressive overload to continue challenging your muscles.

🌀Functional Flexibility🌀
✨Simulates Real Movements✨
Resistance bands can be used to simulate real-life movements, enhancing functional flexibility. This is particularly beneficial for athletes, acrobats, dancers or individuals aiming for extreme flexibility in specific activities or sports.

🌀Injury Prevention🌀
✨Joint Support✨
Using resistance bands in flexibility training can provide gentle support to joints, helping to prevent injury. The controlled resistance can also contribute to better joint stability, which is crucial for maintaining flexibility safely.

Contortion Creative Block 😖

First, WHYYYYYYY 😭:
Internal barriers to creativity often stem from fear of failure, self-doubt, or perfectionism. These self-imposed obstacles can hinder creative expression as individuals may be overly critical, cautious, or hesitant to take risks. Overthinking and a fixed mindset can also contribute to getting in one’s own way by stifling the flow of ideas. Cultivating a positive mindset, embracing imperfection, allowing room for experimentation and playfulness can help overcome these hurdles and foster a more open, creative process.

Something to chew on: 🤔

✨ A gentle connection exists between the playfulness in your daily life and your artistic expression. When life feels less playful, it might inadvertently foster a more serious mindset, which can affect your creative flow. Art loves spontaneity, curiosity, and an open spirit. If these feel a bit distant due to life’s seriousness, it might reflect in your art. Kindly consider weaving playfulness into your daily moments – it’s like a sprinkle of magic that can breathe freedom, joy, and creativity into your artistic endeavors.

Remember, creativity is a journey, and feeling lost is a natural part of it. Embrace the uncertainty, and trust that each step contributes to your creative evolution.
